\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:Introduction}

Over the past three decades, \textbf{credit derivatives} have become increasingly common tools for finanical institutions that wish to pass on \textbf{credit risk} to investors who accept that risk in exchange for interest. To put it simply, credit risk is the possibility that a borrower will \textbf{default} on her loan, or not pay it back. In this paper, we will focus on \textbf{credit default swaps} (CDS), a type of credit derivative that has become quite popular among pension funds, hedge funds, and investment banks, among other financial institutions. We will explain the mechanics of this financial product and show how this \textbf{CDS} package can be used to manipulate and calcuate relevant CDS information. 

CDS originated in the late 1980s and were popularized by a team at J.P. Morgan that included Blythe Masters \citep{cdsOrigins, blythe}. Many different types of CDS have since emerged including basket default swaps (BDSs), index CDS, credit-linked notes, etc. \citep{jk}. In this \textbf{CDS} package, we focus on calculations related to single-name, or corporate, credit default swaps.

\section{CDS Basics}
\label{sec:CDSBasics}

\subsection{An Example: Property Insurance}
\label{sec:PropInsurance}

In order to understand this type of exchange, let's first talk about a simpler from of purchasing protection: property insurance. 

Suppose that person owns a \$100,000 house and wants to buy property insurance for the whole house for one year, from January 1 to December 31. For such a purchase, an insurance company charges a fee of \$1,000. Call this \$1,000 the premium. In exchange for this premium payment, the insurance company agrees to monetarily compensate for any property damage for the next year. 

%% For example, if a house fire occurs during that year; then, the insurance company is obligation to pay \$100,000 to the insurance buyer. Otherwise, the insurance company doesn't have to pay anything.

Let's say that the insurance buyer has to pay the premium (\$1,000) at the beginning of the coverage period, January 1. Let's also assume that, in this case of property damage, the insurance company pays out the compensational amount at the end of the year (Decemeber 31) and interest rates are 0\%. Examining the agreement's cash flows, we can see that the insurance buyer pays a \$1,000 premium on January 1 for property insurance for that year, and if, for example, a house fire occurs during that year, the insurance company pays the buyer a compensational amount of \$100,000 on December 31. Note that if there is no property damage that year, then the insurance company pockets the \$1,000 premium payment and doesn't have to pay anything in return. 

As such, before making this deal, both parties would want to consider the probability of property damage for that year. If, for example, the house owner was extremely confident that the house would not be damaged, and thus believed the probability of damage to essentially be 0\%, then he would not want to make this deal. The only cash flow between the two parties would be the \$1,000 premium payment out of \emph{his} pocket for the one-year coverage! Similarly, if the insurance company thought it was extremely likely that the house would get damaged---maybe it's near a body of water and it's hurricane season---then the insurance company would probably not want to make this deal. In that case, the compensational payment would greatly outweigh the premuim payment, and the insurance company would lose money.

In such a scenario, what probability of property damage would make both parties agree to this deal? In other words, what probability of damage would render the \textbf{expected cash flows} for both parties equal? 

To answer this question, we need to first determine the amount that each party expects to pay. The insurance buyer expects to pay a \$1,000 premium on January 1, regardless of whether damage occurs or not. The insurance company's payment of \$100,000 is contingent upon property damage; otherwise, it's \$0. Thus, if "P" is the probability of damage, we can say the following: 

\begin{equation}
 \begin{aligned}
   {\rm Insurance\hspace{3pt}company's\hspace{3pt}expected\hspace{3pt}payment = P * \$100,000}
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation} 

To determine the "fair" probability of damage at which both parties would agree to this deal, we set the expected cash flows of each party equal to each other:  
 
\begin{equation}
 \begin{aligned}
   {\rm Insurance\hspace{3pt}buyer's\hspace{3pt}expected\hspace{3pt}cash\hspace{3pt}flow = Insurance\hspace{3pt}company's\hspace{3pt}expected\hspace{3pt}cash\hspace{3pt}flow}
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
 \begin{aligned}
   {\rm -\hspace{3pt}\$1,000 + (P * {\$100,000})  = \$1,000 - (P * {\$100,000})}
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}

As we can see, the insurance buyer expects to pay the \$1,000 premium and potentially receive the \$100,000 (based on the probability of damage) and the insurance company expects to receive \$1,000 premium and potentially pay the \$100,000 compensation payment. Solving for "P", we get:

\begin{equation}
 \begin{aligned}
   {\rm (2)(P * {\$100,000})  =  (2)(\$1,000)}
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
 \begin{aligned}
   {\rm P * {\$100,000}  = \$1,000}
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}

Thus, we can see that if "P" is .01, or 1\%, then this would be considered a fair deal for both parties; the expected cash flows are equal.

Note that the above calculations assume that the compensational amount paid in case of damage is always equal to the monetary amount the buyer bought insurance for. However, what if, say, a house fire occured and only damaged half of the house? Then, our example insurance company would not have to pay the full value of \$100,000.

So, when the two parties---the insurance buyer and the insurance company---initiate the insurance agreement, they need to agree on what kind of damage merits the payment of the full \$100,000, and what doesn't. They would also have to come to a consensus on the definition of "property damage," and how to measure it (how does the insurance company know that there has actually been a fire?). Clearly, this highlights the importance of a contract that specifies the terms of the agreement.

Note also that, even though the house is worth \$100,000, the insurance buyer could choose to buy insurance for only half the house---so only \$50,000 worth of the house. 

\subsection{Simple One-Period Case}
\label{sec:OnePeriod}

Instead of buying insurance against property damage, let's consider buying insurance against a company's inability to meet its obligations. For example, let's say that a portfolio manager owns \$100,000 worth of bonds from Alcoa, a company, and she is concerned that Alcoa won't return the money she lent. In other words, she is concerned that Alcoa will \textbf{default} on its bonds---not pay them back---and that Alcoa may even go bankrupt in the next year. So, she enters a one-year CDS agreement with an investment bank---say, J.P. Morgan.

What does this mean? Well, for simplicity's sake, we'll keep the same timeline (January 1 - December 31) and numerical figures from our property insurance example. We'll also stick with the assumption that interest rates are 0\%. The portfolio manager agrees to pay a \textbf{coupon} (equivalent to the premium in our property insurance example) of 1\% (or 100 basis points (bps)) of the \$100,000, known as the \textbf{notional amount} of this CDS. Thus, the portfolio manager pays \$1,000 on January 1 in exchange for protection against default of Alcoa for that year. This side of the CDS contract is known as the \textbf{premium leg}, and the portfolio manager is known as the \textbf{protection buyer}. 

The other side of the CDS agreement is known as the \textbf{protection leg} and involves J.P. Morgan, the \textbf{protection seller}. If Alcoa defaults, then J.P. Morgan must pay \$100,000 to the portfolio manager on December 31 of that year. Note that Alcoa is known as the \textbf{reference entity} in this CDS since it is the company from which the protection buyer desires protection. The portfolio manager's specific Alcoa bonds are known collectively as the \textbf{reference obligation}.

%% \begin{figure}[H]
%% \centering
%% \includegraphics[width=4in, height=1in]{images/CDSmechanics.png}
%% \caption{Cash flows in a single-name CDS contract.}
%% \label{fig:cashFlow}
%% \end{figure}

Is this agreement a fair deal? Well, like our property insurance example, it depends on a probability: the \textbf{probability of default}. To solve for the probability of default that would render this deal fair, we need to equate the cash flows from the portfolio manager (left side of equation) and J.P. Morgan (right side of equation). In this equation, "C" stands for coupon payment, "P" is the probability of default, and "V" is the notional amount.

\begin{equation}
 \begin{aligned}
   {\rm Insurance\hspace{3pt}buyer's\hspace{3pt}expected\hspace{3pt}cash\hspace{3pt}flow = Insurance\hspace{3pt}company's\hspace{3pt}expected\hspace{3pt}cash\hspace{3pt}flow}
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
 \begin{aligned}
   {\rm -\hspace{3pt}C + (P * V)  = C - (P * V)}
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}

The left side shows how the portfolio manager has to pay the coupon, "C", but could receive the protection leg of "V", depending on P. The right indicates the converse; J.P. Morgan will receive the coupon payment, "C", but could potentially have to pay the protection leg of "V", depending on "P". Plugging in known values ("C" = \$1,000 and "V" = \$100,000), we get:

\begin{equation}
 \begin{aligned}
   {\rm -\hspace{3pt}\$1,000 + (P * {\$100,000})  = \$1,000 - (P * {\$100,000})}
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}

This is the same equation as in the property insurance example! This shouldn't be too surprising, though, since we used the same numerical figures in this example. Since these equations are the same, we know that if the probability of default is 1\%, then this deal is considered fair.

\subsubsection{Interest Rate}
\label{sec:InterestRate}

%% Not sure what sort of interest rate definition we should provide at this point. Singular or plural?

Up until now, we have assumed that the interest rate is 0\% for our CDS example. The \textbf{interest rate} is a benchmark rate that represents the return that investors can expect without much risk. How might the cash flows in the CDS agreement change if the interest rate was \emph{not} 0\%---instead, say 2\%?

First, let's review our CDS agreement: the portfolio manager pays the premium leg on January 1 and J.P. Morgan pays the protection leg (if Alcoa defaults) on December 31. J.P. Morgan receives the \$1,000 coupon a full \emph{year} before the portfolio manager would receive the \$100,000 payment if Alcoa defaults. In an environment where the interest rate is 2\%, J.P. Morgan could theoretically invest the \$1,000 sum starting January 1 and earn interest for that year:

\begin{equation}
 \begin{aligned}
  {\rm Coupon\hspace{3pt}with\hspace{3pt}Interest = \frac{\$1,000}{(1 + .02)} = \$1,020} 
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}

By December 31, the \$1,000 could grow to \$1,020, which gives J.P. Morgan an extra \$20 that the portfolio manager won't receive because she doesn't get a payment---if at all---until the end of the year. As such, the \$1,000 coupon has more value \emph{per} \emph{dollar} than the \$100,000 payment. If the interest rate is not 0\%, then we need to adjust the cash flows accordingly to account for the extra money that J.P. Morgan gains. Otherwise, the portfolio manager's expected cash flow is larger that that of J.P. Morgan---and why would the portfolio manager want to enter this agreement if it were unfair on her own end?

To alter the cash flows in a way that once again creates a fair deal for both parties, we must discount our previously calculated coupon by the interest rate. In this context, the rate we are using to discount the coupon can be called the \textbf{discount rate}. In other words, the coupon should be an amount that, if invested at the current interest rate of 2\% for one year, would equal \$1,000. Below represents those calculations (with the final result rounded to the nearest cent):

\begin{equation}
 \begin{aligned}
  {\rm Discounted\hspace{3pt}Coupon = \frac{\$1,000}{(1 + .02)} = \$980.39} 
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}

Thus, the new coupon value that would account for a world in which the interest rate is 2\% is \$980.39. If the portfolio manager gives J.P. Morgan \$980.39 on January 1, J.P. Morgan can invest that sum and grow it to \$1,000 by December 31, when J.P. Morgan would pay the protection leg if necessary. 

For a generic case, here are the cash flows when the interest rate is not 0\%. "P", again, refers to the probability of default; "V" represents the notional amount; "i" stands for the interest rate; and "C" is the coupon payment (before discounting).

\begin{equation}
 \begin{aligned}
  {\rm -\hspace{3pt}\frac{C}{(1 + i)} + (P * V) = \frac{C}{(1 + i)} - (P * V)} 
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}
Plugging in known values:
\begin{equation}
 \begin{aligned}
  {\rm -\hspace{3pt}\frac{\$1,000}{(1 + .02)} + (P * \$100,000) = \frac{\$1,000}{(1 + .02)} - (P * \$100,000)} 
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}
Eventually, we get:
\begin{equation}
 \begin{aligned}
  {\rm (P * \$100,000) = \$980.39}  
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}

Now that the coupon rate has changed to adjust for an environment with 2\% interest rate, the probability of default that both parties would want to agree on to make this deal changes, as well. As we can see, P = .98\% (as opposed to 1\% in an environment with 0\% interest rate).

\subsubsection{Recovery Rate}
\label{sec:RecoveryRate}

Recall that in our property insurance example, we mentioned that some cases---such as a house fire that burns half of a house---may not merit a full compensation payment equal to the notional amount (in that case, \$100,000). Similarly, when a company defaults, it can usually retain some of its assets and distribute that money among those to whom the company owes money. In other words, companies that default are usually able to partially compensate its bondholders. In such a scenario, a protection seller for that company would only have to pay the fraction of the notional amount that the reference entity, or company did \emph{not} pay, in the case of default.

Let's exemplify using our simple, one-period CDS: suppose that Alcoa defaults during the one-year CDS contract, but it's able to give the portfolio manager \$50,000 of the \$100,000 it owes her. In that case, J.P. Morgan would only have to pay the portfolio manager another \$50,000 (not the notional amount of \$100,000) to compensate for her monetary loss from Alcoa's default. The ratio of the amount a bondholder receives after a company's default compared to the amount the bondholder \emph{should} have received (with no default) is known as the \textbf{recovery rate}. So, in the example described above, the recovery rate is 50\%.

Let's assume that, once again, the interest rate is 0\%, and thus not a factor in the expected cash flows for the portfolio manager and J.P. Morgan. A fair deal is one in which these two values are equal. In a CDS in which the company is expected to have a recovery rate, we could lay out the cash flows as in the following equation. Like before, the left side represents the cash flows for the portfolio manager and the right side represents the cash flows for J.P. Morgan. (Note that "r" refers to the recovery rate and, as before, "P" is the probability of default, "C" is the coupon payment, and "V" is the notional amount.) 

\begin{equation}
 \begin{aligned}
   {\rm - C + (P)([1-r]*V) = C - (P)([1-r]*V)}
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}

Although this equation may look more complicated than other equations we've introduced, note that this equation is very similar to Equation 6. In fact, the only difference (multiplying "V" by (1-r)) accounts for the fact that the protection leg is the \emph{fraction} of the notional amount that the protection seller has to pay (since there is a non-zero recovery rate). Since recovery rate specifies the fraction of the notional amount that the \emph{ reference entity} is able to pay, we need to multiply "V" by (1-r), not just "r", to find the true value of the protection leg.

To solve for the probability of default that would make this deal fair, let's plug in the known values in the case where the recovery rate is 50\%:

\begin{equation}
 \begin{aligned}
   {\rm - \$1,000 + (P)([1 - 0.5]*\$100,000) = \$1,000 - (P)([1 - 0.5]*\$100,000)}
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}
After combining like terms, dividing both sides by 2 and simplifying, we get:
\begin{equation}
 \begin{aligned}
   {\rm P * \$50,000 = \$1,000}
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}

In such a scenario, the default probability that both parties would need to agree to for this to be fair is 2\%.

\subsubsection{Upfront payment}
\label{sec:Upfront}

Let's go back to our simple CDS example---0\% interest rate, 0\% recovery rate. So far, we have looked at different scenarios and calculated an ideal probability of default which would make both parties happy. Or, at least, the CDS agreement would be fair. In the simple one-period CDS example, this ideal probability was calculated to be 1\%.

However, what if the \emph{actual} probability of default is 2\%? 0.5\%? Clearly, this is no longer a fair deal. How do we construct a fair deal with equal expected cash flows from the portfolio manager and from J.P. Morgan?

Let's consider the case in which the actual probability of defaut is 0.5\%. The expected payment of the portfolio manager at the end of the year will be greater than J.P. Morgans's expected payment since the probability of default (and thus the probility that J.P. Morgan will have to pay out any money at all) is less than the probability that makes the deal fair: 1\%. A simple solution to this issue would be to lower the portfolio manager's coupon. 

This is what we start with (assuming an ideal probability of default of 1\%):

\begin{equation}
 \begin{aligned}
   {\rm -\hspace{3pt}\$1,000 + ((P = 1\%) * {\$100,000})  = \$1,000 - ((P = 1\%) * {\$100,000})}
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}

And this is how we need to adjust if the actual probability of default is 0.5\%:

\begin{equation}
 \begin{aligned}
   {\rm -\hspace{3pt}\$500 + ((P = 0.5\%) * {\$100,000})  = \$500 - ((P = .5\%) * {\$100,000})}
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}

Since the probability of default and the coupon are directly related, we divide the coupon in half (from \$1,000 to \$500) when and if the probability of default is divided in half (from 1\% to 0.5\%). This is surely a viable solution.

However, let's say that, by CDS market conventions, all CDS are traded at a standard coupon of 1\%. If the \emph{actual} probability of Alcoa's default is less 1\% (0.5\% in this case), how do we modify the CDS agreement to once again make it a fair trade for both parties?

The answer lies in an \textbf{upfront payment}---a payment made from one party to the other at the beginning of a contract (in this case, January 1). If the probability of Alcoa's default is 0.5\%, then J.P. Morgan has to compensate the protection buyer for paying a coupon of 1\% instead of a coupon of 0.5\%. Since the difference between the protection buyer's fair payment (\$500 at 0.5\%) and the payment she has to make due to convention (\$1,000 at 1\%) is \$500, J.P. Morgan's upfront payment to the protection buyer should be \$500. Another way of way of thinking about the upfront payment is to consider the difference in expected cash flows between the two parties. Since J.P. Morgan's expected cash flow is larger than that of the portfolio manager, the upfront payment ("X") is positive on the left side of the equation (the portfolio manager's expected cash flow) and negative on the other side (J.P. Morgan's expected cash flow). As before, "C" designates the coupon payment, "P" is the probability of default, and "V" is the notional amount.

\begin{equation}
 \begin{aligned}
   {\rm X - C + (P * V) = C - (P * V)}
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}

Plugging in known values:

\begin{equation}
 \begin{aligned}
   {\rm X - \$1,000 + (.005 * \$100,000) = \$1,000 - (.005 * \$100,000) - X}
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}

Simplifying:

\begin{equation}
 \begin{aligned}
   {\rm (2)X + (2)(\$500) = (2)*\$1,000}
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}

As such, \$500 is the correct upfront payment for this situation.

That way, with an upfront payment, the two parties can trade according to CDS convention and still create a fair deal in which the expected payments from each party are equal. Let's assume that both the upfront payment and the coupon payment are made at the same time: on January 1, the first day of the one-year contract. In this case, since the portfolio manager would have to pay J.P. Morgan \$1,000, and J.P. Morgan would have to pay the buyer \$500, the two parties can just agree to have one equivalent cash flow: the protection buyer paying \$500 to J.P. Morgan.

Note that we need to know what the probability of default is in order to calculate an upfront payment. Conversely, if we only know the upfront payment, we can calculate the implied probability of default that both parties agree to. 

