\subsubsection{Accrued Coupon}
\label{sec:AccruedCoupon}

Again, back to our simple, one-period CDS example. We have so far assumed that our CDS agreement between the portfolio manager and J.P. Morgan begins on January 1 and ends on December 31 of the same year. However, what if this agreement wasn't made exactly on January 1? What if it was made halfway through the year, on June 30? Let's assume the probability of default for those six months is indeed 1\%---the probability that renders the CDS contract fair. Under our current description of a CDS agreement, this implies that the portfolio manager would have to pay the same coupon of 1\% (\$1,000) on January 1 for only receiving six months (instead of one year) of protection coverage. Now, the expected payment of the portfolio manager is greater than that of J.P. Morgan.

To account for this, let's first calculate the amount of the coupon that the portfolio manager is unfairly paying---that is, the fraction of the coupon payment that accounts for the first six months of the year (January 1 - June 30), which she does not receive coverage for. This fraction of the coupon payment is known as the \textbf{accrued coupon}.

\begin{equation}
 \begin{aligned}
  {\rm Accrued = \frac{180}{360}*\frac{1.0}{100}*\$100,000 = \$500}
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}

Note that we just divided the coupon payment in half, which makes sense since January 1 - June 30 consists of half of the year. Note also that we are dividing 180 by 360 instead of 365 in the above calculation. This particular CDS contract can be said to have a 30/365 \textbf{day count convention}, meaning that the accrued coupon calculations are based on the assumptions that there are 30 days in a month and 360 days in a year. This simplication makes calculations much easier. 

%% Why, other than for simplicity's sake, do people use the 30/365 day count convention?

The portfolio manager does not want (and understandably does not have the obligation) to pay for the six months she did not receive coverage for. Instead, it is \emph{J.P. Morgan} who pays the accrued coupon to the portfolio manager; after this adjustment, the expected payments from each party are once again equal. Since the portfolio manager is already paying J.P. Morgan a coupon of \$1,000 and now, in this case where the CDS contract initiates on June 30, J.P. Morgan owes the portfolio manager \$500 of accrued interest, the two parties can agree to one equivalent cash flow: \$500 from the portfolio manager to J.P. Morgan.

Note that accrued coupon only becomes relevant when the contract does not initiate on a coupon payment date. In the real-world CDS market, there are four dates each year---instead of, in our example, the one date of January 1---when coupon payments can be made. These dates are known as \textbf{roll dates} and comprise the following: March 20, June 20, September 20, and December 20. As we proceed with our simple CDS example, however, we'll continue with the assumption that January 1 is the one and only "roll date."  

\subsubsection{Summary}
\label{sec:Sum}

So far, we have introduced a simple, one-period CDS agreement between a portfolio manager and J.P. Morgan. We then introduced four factors that affect the expected cash flows for both parties: interest rate, recovery rate, upfront payment, and accrued coupon.

In a real-world scenario, we'd have to look at \emph{all} these factors at the same time, and come up with a way to show cash flows that take all four factors into account.

Combining Equations 1, 2, and 3, we get a master equation that accounts for interest rate ("i"), recovery rate ("r"), and upfront payment ("X"). Accrued coupon can be calculated separately based on the date the CDS was initiated. (As before, "C" stands for the coupon payment, "P" for the probability of default, and "V" for the notional amount.)

\begin{equation}
 \begin{aligned}
   {\rm X -\hspace{3pt}\frac{C}{(1 + i)} + (P)([1-r] * V)  = \frac{C}{(1 + i)} - (P)([1-r] * V) - X}
    \end{aligned}
\end{equation}

Note that for any established CDS contract, the two unknown variables are "P" and "X": the probability of default and the upfront payment. You need one to calculate the other, and vice versa.

By looking at this equation, we can see that in order for any CDS trades to be made, there needs be a general consensus on the value of the recovery rate for a certain reference entity and the value of the interest rate at a given time. In the CDS market, these values are determined and set by an regulatory organization known as the International Swaps and Derivatives Association (ISDA). 

ISDA also regulates the types of coupons that people can use in a CDS. In April 2009 in North America, the ISDA introduced a series of mandatory modifications to the CDS contract known as the "Big Bang" protocol. Under the new rules, coupon rates were standardized in North America and Europe starting June 2009. Dealers now had to quote standard coupons of 100bps or 500bps in North America, or 25bps, 100bps, 500bps or 1000bps in Europe, and all coupons were paid quarterly on one of the four roll dates. 

%% ACCRUED INTEREST + DISCOUNTED RATES + UPFRONT PAYMENTS: Thus, if the CDS contract was initiated on June 30, then the total upfront payment made by J.P. Morgan to the portfolio manager would be \$495 (which is equal to \$500/(1+ 1\%) rounded to nearest dollar) + \$250 = \$745. This value is known as the \textbf{dirty upfront}, since it specifies the actual upfront payment that (in this case) the protection seller will pay the protection buyer. The \textbf{clean upfront}, on the other hand, does not take accrued interest into account, and (in this case) is equal to \$495. Note that the portion of the upfront payment that accounts for a lower probability of default than 1\% is discounted by the discount rate, and the portion that accounts for the accured interest is not. This is because the accrued interest should be worth \$250 \emph{now} (June 30), and the other portion of the upfront payment should be worth \$500 on December 31.

\subsection{Two-Period Case}
\label{sec:TwoPeriod}

Up until now, we have described various aspects of a CDS agreement that has one coupon payment on January 1. However, most CDS include more than one coupon payment. Let's explore an agreement which is the same as the simple, one-period CDS example in the previous section with the exception of the duration: two years. This CDS has two coupon payments: one on January 1 of the first year and one on January 1 of the second year. For this case, let's assume that the interest rate is 0\% and the probability of default is constant for both years of the contract. If the notional amount is still \$100,000 and the standardized coupon is still 1\% (so the buyer will make two \$1,000 coupon payments), then the probability of default would have to be 2\% for this to be a fair deal (plugging in values for Equation BLANK):

\begin{equation}
 \begin{aligned}
